c is used for ch, g, qu, s, t; it is also sometimes inserted (e. g. unexisti), and sometimes omitted.

e is used not only for ae, but also for e and oe.

f is used for ff, and for ph.

ff is used for f.

g is occasionally used for i (e. g. genuam=ianuam).

h is sometimes prefixed, inserted, and omitted.

i is used for ae, for e (very frequently), and u, rarely for g, and often for y: it is sometimes doubled, sometimes omitted.

l is used for 11, and ll for 1. ’

m is used sor mm.

n is used for nn, sometimes inserted before s.

o is used for u (very frequently).

oe is used for ae, and for e.

p is used for b, and for pp: sometimes inserted and sometimes omitted in words like sollempnis.

qu is used for c, and for ch.

s is used for c; sometimes for ss; sometimes inserted, some- times not inserted, in such words as exequi.

t is used sor c, d, th, tt, and sometimes doubled.

u is sometimes used for i, and frequently for 0.

v is used for b, and for f.

y is used frequently for i.

The assimilation of consonants in composition sometimes takes place, but they are perhaps more commonly left unassimilated.
